blocks.name: elee
blocks.content: Membership in a Euclidean space. We define Euclidean space here using Cartesian coordinates over ` N ` space. We later abstract away from this using Tarski's geometry axioms, so this exact definition is unimportant. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 3-Jun-2013.)
blocks.origin:
thm elee(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wcel(c0, cn), wb(wcel(c1, cfv(cee, c0)), wf(c1, co(nat1, cfz, c0), cr)))
} = {
  syl6bb(wcel(c0, cn), wcel(c1, cfv(cee, c0)), wf(c1, co(nat1, cfz, c0), cr), wcel(c1, co(cr, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, c0))))
  eleq2d(c1, cfv(cee, c0), co(cr, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, c0)), wcel(c0, cn))
  fvmpt(hs0, c0, cn, cee, co(cr, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, c0)), co(cr, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, cv(hs0))))
  oveq2d(cr, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, cv(hs0)), co(nat1, cfz, c0), wceq(cv(hs0), c0))
  oveq2(cv(hs0), c0, nat1, cfz)
  df-ee(hs0)
  ovex(cr, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, c0))
  elmap(c1, cr, co(nat1, cfz, c0))
  reex()
  ovex(nat1, cfz, c0)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.c(cn)
  diff.hs0.c(co(cr, cmap, co(nat1, cfz, c0)))
}
blocks.pretty:
thm elee(class c0, class c1) {
  ⊢ (c0 ∈ ℕ →(c1 ∈(EE ` c0)↔(c1 :(1[...]c0)→ ℝ)))
} = {
  syl6bb(c0 ∈ ℕ, c1 ∈(EE ` c0), (c1 :(1[...]c0)→ ℝ), c1 ∈(ℝ[↦](1[...]c0)))
  eleq2d(c1, (EE ` c0), (ℝ[↦](1[...]c0)), c0 ∈ ℕ)
  fvmpt(hs0, c0, cn, cee, (ℝ[↦](1[...]c0)), (ℝ[↦](1[...]hs0)))
  oveq2d(cr, cmap, (1[...]hs0), (1[...]c0), hs0 = c0)
  oveq2(hs0, c0, nat1, cfz)
  df-ee(hs0)
  ovex(cr, cmap, (1[...]c0))
  elmap(c1, cr, (1[...]c0))
  reex()
  ovex(nat1, cfz, c0)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.c(cn)
  diff.hs0.c((ℝ[↦](1[...]c0)))
}

blocks.name: brcgr
blocks.content: The binary relation form of the congruence predicate. The statement ` <. A , B >. Cgr <. C , D >. ` should be read informally as "the ` N ` dimensional point ` A ` is as far from ` B ` as ` C ` is from ` D ` , or "the line segment ` A B ` is congruent to the line segment ` C D ` . This particular definition is encapsulated by Tarski's axioms later on. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 3-Jun-2013.)
blocks.origin:
